    "procedure_examples": [
      {
        "id": "G0007",
        "name": "APT28",
        "url": "/groups/G0007",
        "description": "<p><a href=\"/groups/G0007\">APT28</a> has used compromised Office 365 service accounts with Global Administrator privileges to collect email from user inboxes.<sup><a href=\"https://media.defense.gov/2021/Jul/01/2002753896/-1/-1/1/CSA_GRU_GLOBAL_BRUTE_FORCE_CAMPAIGN_UOO158036-21.PDF\" target=\"_blank\">[4]</a></sup></p>"
      },
      {
        "id": "G0016",
        "name": "APT29",
        "url": "/groups/G0016",
        "description": "<p><a href=\"/groups/G0016\">APT29</a> has gained access to a global administrator account in Azure AD and has used <code>Service Principal</code> credentials in Exchange.<sup><a href=\"https://www.mandiant.com/resources/blog/apt29-continues-targeting-microsoft\" target=\"_blank\">[5]</a></sup><sup><a href=\"https://www.mandiant.com/resources/blog/unc3524-eye-spy-email\" target=\"_blank\">[6]</a></sup></p>"
      },
      {
        "id": "G0064",
        "name": "APT33",
        "url": "/groups/G0064",
        "description": "<p><a href=\"/groups/G0064\">APT33</a> has used compromised Office 365 accounts in tandem with <a href=\"/software/S0358\">Ruler</a> in an attempt to gain control of endpoints.<sup><a href=\"https://www.microsoft.com/security/blog/2020/06/18/inside-microsoft-threat-protection-mapping-attack-chains-from-cloud-to-endpoint/\" target=\"_blank\">[7]</a></sup></p>"
      },
      {
        "id": "G1023",
        "name": "APT5",
        "url": "/groups/G1023",
        "description": "<p><a href=\"/groups/G1023\">APT5</a> has accessed Microsoft M365 cloud environments using stolen credentials. <sup><a href=\"https://www.mandiant.com/resources/blog/updates-on-chinese-apt-compromising-pulse-secure-vpn-devices\" target=\"_blank\">[8]</a></sup></p>"
      },
      {
        "id": "C0027",
        "name": "C0027",
        "url": "/campaigns/C0027",
        "description": "<p>During <a href=\"https://attack.mitre.org/campaigns/C0027\">C0027</a>, <a href=\"/groups/G1015\">Scattered Spider</a> leveraged compromised credentials from victim users to authenticate to Azure tenants.<sup><a href=\"https://www.crowdstrike.com/blog/analysis-of-intrusion-campaign-targeting-telecom-and-bpo-companies/\" target=\"_blank\">[9]</a></sup></p>"
      },
      {
        "id": "G0004",
        "name": "Ke3chang",
        "url": "/groups/G0004",
        "description": "<p><a href=\"/groups/G0004\">Ke3chang</a> has used compromised credentials to sign into victims’ Microsoft 365 accounts.<sup><a href=\"https://www.microsoft.com/security/blog/2021/12/06/nickel-targeting-government-organizations-across-latin-america-and-europe\" target=\"_blank\">[10]</a></sup></p>"
      },
      {
        "id": "G1004",
        "name": "LAPSUS$",
        "url": "/groups/G1004",
        "description": "<p><a href=\"/groups/G1004\">LAPSUS$</a> has used compromised credentials to access cloud assets within a target organization.<sup><a href=\"https://www.microsoft.com/security/blog/2022/03/22/dev-0537-criminal-actor-targeting-organizations-for-data-exfiltration-and-destruction/\" target=\"_blank\">[11]</a></sup></p>"
      },
      {
        "id": "S1091",
        "name": "Pacu",
        "url": "/software/S1091",
        "description": "<p><a href=\"/software/S1091\">Pacu</a> leverages valid cloud accounts to perform most of its operations.<sup><a href=\"https://github.com/RhinoSecurityLabs/pacu\" target=\"_blank\">[12]</a></sup></p>"
      },
      {
        "id": "S0683",
        "name": "Peirates",
        "url": "/software/S0683",
        "description": "<p><a href=\"/software/S0683\">Peirates</a> can use stolen service account tokens to perform its operations.<sup><a href=\"https://github.com/inguardians/peirates\" target=\"_blank\">[13]</a></sup></p>"
      },
      {
        "id": "S0684",
        "name": "ROADTools",
        "url": "/software/S0684",
        "description": "<p><a href=\"/software/S0684\">ROADTools</a> leverages valid cloud credentials to perform enumeration operations using the internal Azure AD Graph API.<sup><a href=\"https://dirkjanm.io/introducing-roadtools-and-roadrecon-azure-ad-exploration-framework/\" target=\"_blank\">[14]</a></sup></p>"
      },
      {
        "id": "C0024",
        "name": "SolarWinds Compromise",
        "url": "/campaigns/C0024",
        "description": "<p>During the <a href=\"https://attack.mitre.org/campaigns/C0024\">SolarWinds Compromise</a>, <a href=\"/groups/G0016\">APT29</a> used a compromised O365 administrator account to create a new Service Principal.<sup><a href=\"https://www.crowdstrike.com/blog/observations-from-the-stellarparticle-campaign/\" target=\"_blank\">[15]</a></sup></p>"
      }
    ],
    "mitigations": [
      {
        "id": "M1036",
        "name": "Account Use Policies",
        "url": "/mitigations/M1036",
        "description": "<p>Use conditional access policies to block logins from non-compliant devices or from outside defined organization IP ranges.<sup><a href=\"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/active-directory/conditional-access/concept-conditional-access-policy-common\" target=\"_blank\">[16]</a></sup></p>"
      },
      {
        "id": "M1015",
        "name": "Active Directory Configuration",
        "url": "/mitigations/M1015",
        "description": "<p>Disable legacy authentication, which does not support MFA, and require the use of modern authentication protocols instead. </p>"
      },
      {
        "id": "M1032",
        "name": "Multi-factor Authentication",
        "url": "/mitigations/M1032",
        "description": "<p>Use multi-factor authentication for cloud accounts, especially privileged accounts. This can be implemented in a variety of forms (e.g. hardware, virtual, SMS), and can also be audited using administrative reporting features.<sup><a href=\"https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/security/newly-updated-features-in-the-aws-iam-console-help-you-adhere-to-iam-best-practices/\" target=\"_blank\">[17]</a></sup></p>"
      },
      {
        "id": "M1027",
        "name": "Password Policies",
        "url": "/mitigations/M1027",
        "description": "<p>Ensure that cloud accounts, particularly privileged accounts, have complex, unique passwords across all systems on the network. Passwords and access keys should be rotated regularly. This limits the amount of time credentials can be used to access resources if a credential is compromised without your knowledge. Cloud service providers may track access key age to help audit and identify keys that may need to be rotated.<sup><a href=\"https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/security/newly-updated-features-in-the-aws-iam-console-help-you-adhere-to-iam-best-practices/\" target=\"_blank\">[17]</a></sup></p>"
      },
      {
        "id": "M1026",
        "name": "Privileged Account Management",
        "url": "/mitigations/M1026",
        "description": "<p>Review privileged cloud account permission levels routinely to look for those that could allow an adversary to gain wide access, such as Global Administrator and Privileged Role Administrator in Azure AD.<sup><a href=\"https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/dn535501.aspx\" target=\"_blank\">[18]</a></sup><sup><a href=\"https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/dn487450.aspx\" target=\"_blank\">[19]</a></sup><sup><a href=\"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/security/benchmark/azure/baselines/aad-security-baseline\" target=\"_blank\">[20]</a></sup></p><p> These reviews should also check if new privileged cloud accounts have been created that were not authorized. For example, in Azure AD environments configure alerts to notify when accounts have gone many days without using privileged roles, as these roles may be able to be removed.<sup><a href=\"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/security/benchmark/azure/baselines/aad-security-baseline\" target=\"_blank\">[21]</a></sup></p><p>Consider using temporary, just-in-time (JIT) privileged access to Azure AD resources rather than permanently assigning privileged roles.<sup><a href=\"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/security/benchmark/azure/baselines
